					<description><![CDATA[<p>Corgi has announced a $160 million Series B funding round. The investment comes just 4 months after the company’s A round, propelling Corgi&#8217;s valuation to $1.3 billion. The round was</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/corgi-raises-160m-to-expand-ai-insurance-platform/" data-wpel-link="internal">Corgi Raises $160M to Expand AI Insurance Platform</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.corgi.insure/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Corgi </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">has announced a $160 million Series B </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/illoca-raises-13m-to-reinvent-architectural-design/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">round. The investment comes just 4 months after the company’s A round, propelling Corgi&#8217;s valuation to $1.3 billion. The round was led by TCV, the growth-stage giant that was an early investor in Netflix and Airbnb.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The fundraise was supported by a deep bench of both existing and new investors, including Y Combinator, Kindred Ventures, Contrary, Leblon Capital and Oliver Jung. This most recent round brings Corgi&#8217;s capital to more than $268 million.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Rewriting the Insurance Stack</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Founded in 2024 by Nico Laqua (CEO) and Emily Yuan (COO), a former product manager at OpenAI, Corgi has distinguished itself by being an AI-native full-stack carrier. Unlike traditional insurtech firms that often act as digital brokers for legacy insurance giants, Corgi is a licensed carrier that writes its own policies and manages its own risk.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_200852" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-200852" class="size-large wp-image-200852" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Insurance-1024x683.jpg" alt="Insurance" width="1024" height="683" /><p id="caption-attachment-200852" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The core of Corgi’s value proposition is its proprietary AI underwriting layer. By replacing manual audits and slow bureaucratic workflows with real-time risk modelling, the platform can compress the quoting cycle for complex business insurance from several days to under five minutes.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;Insurance is one of the largest industries in the world, yet it is still built on infrastructure from centuries ago,&#8221; said COO Emily Yuan. &#8220;We aren&#8217;t just layering software on top of old systems; we have rebuilt the entire stack from the ground up to enable faster decisions and real-time coverage that actually scales with a business.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News</span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/illoca-raises-13m-to-reinvent-architectural-design/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">: Illoca Raises $13M to Reinvent Architectural Design</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Strategic Expansion: From Tech to Trucking</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The Series B funding represents a major shift towards broader industrial sectors, even though Corgi first established its reputation as a provider of coverage for technology startups, offering modular policies like Cyber Liability, Directors and Officers , and their recently introduced &#8220;AI Liability&#8221; coverage.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company announced that its first major vertical expansion will be into the trucking and logistics industry. Much like the startup sector, trucking involves high-stakes risk profiles that traditional insurers often struggle to price accurately in real-time. Corgi intends to apply its adaptive AI models to create more flexible, data-driven premiums for fleet operators.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;Our mission is to support the real economy,&#8221; CEO Nico Laqua stated. &#8220;Whether it&#8217;s a pre-seed software company or a long-haul trucking fleet, businesses deserve insurance that acts at the speed of compute, not the speed of paperwork.&#8221;</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Disrupting the Incumbents</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Corgi&#8217;s meteoric rise coincides with that of many other traditional carriers pulling back from AI risk: just this week Corgi announced a pioneering AI insurance coverage product that provides protection in case of financial and legal damages caused by an AI malfunction, biased algorithm output, or adversarial attack.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">As both the technology provider and the insurer, with no middleman pain (which results in crushing premiums and slow claims, as a point), Corgi appears to have shown compelling product/market fit after reaching some $40 million of ARR since being fully approved in mid-2025.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">By raising $160 million, Corgi will expand its engineering team threefold, enhance its distribution across the U.S., and continue to build out its underlying AI that enables its automated claims and policy administration.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/corgi-raises-160m-to-expand-ai-insurance-platform/" data-wpel-link="internal">Corgi Raises $160M to Expand AI Insurance Platform</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
